T1  - HOUSEHOLD INTERACTION AND THE LABOR SUPPLY OF MARRIED WOMEN
AU  - Eckstein, Zvi
AU  - Lifshitz, Osnat
Y1  - 2015/05/01
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12110
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 427
EP  - 455
VL  - 56
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12110
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Are changing social norms affecting the employment rates of women? A model is built in which the employment of husbands and wives is the outcome of potentially exogenously determined three different types of household games: the Classical household, where the spouses play a Stackelberg leader game in which the wife's labor supply decision is based on her husband's employment outcome; the Modern household, which is characterized by a symmetric and simultaneous game solved as a Nash equilibrium, and the Cooperative household, where the couple jointly maximizes the weighted sum of their utilities. In all models, husbands? employment is similar whereas wives work much less in Classical households.
ER  - 

