T1  - INFLATION EXPECTATIONS AND BEHAVIOR: DO SURVEY RESPONDENTS ACT ON THEIR BELIEFS?
AU  - Armantier, Olivier
AU  - Bruine de Bruin, Wändi
AU  - Topa, Giorgio
AU  - van der Klaauw, Wilbert
AU  - Zafar, Basit
Y1  - 2015/05/01
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12113
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 505
EP  - 536
VL  - 56
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12113
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We compare the inflation expectations reported by consumers in a survey with their behavior in a financially incentivized investment experiment. The survey is found to be informative in the sense that the beliefs reported by the respondents are correlated with their choices in the experiment. More importantly, we find evidence that most respondents act on their inflation expectations showing patterns consistent with economic theory. Respondents whose behavior cannot be rationalized tend to have lower education and lower numeracy and financial literacy. These findings help confirm the relevance of inflation expectations surveys and provide support to the microfoundations of modern macroeconomic models.
ER  - 

