T1  - DOES IT PAY FOR WOMEN TO VOLUNTEER?
AU  - Sauer, Robert M.
Y1  - 2015/05/01
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12114
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 537
EP  - 564
VL  - 56
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12114
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article estimates the economic and noneconomic returns to volunteering for prime-aged women. Estimates of a DCDP model indicate that an extra year of volunteer experience increases wage offers by 8.5% in future part-time work and by 2.6% in future full-time work. On average, working for free increases lifetime earnings by 16.7%. The economic returns to volunteering are more important than the noneconomic returns in increasing lifetime utility. The model also reveals an adverse selection mechanism into volunteering that helps explain why reduced-form regressions of the returns to working for free will likely be downward biased.
ER  - 

